<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-449-104  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 449 104.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  July 1989 v12 n7 p153(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Modeling molecules. (computer-aided design system helps geneticengineers visualize results of synthetic molecule production)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Webster, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers in biochemistry are using advanced computer graphicsequipment to analyze and measure the composition of complexcompounds and to supplement the traditional 'ball and stick'method of visualizing molecular arrangements.andP;  Computer modelingenables scientists to preview the results of a particularsubstitution and ensure that it fits into the molecule beingstudied.andP;  Novo-Nordisk A/S uses a system based on SiliconGraphics' 10 MIPS 4D/70 GT workstation and Polygen Corp's Charmmmodeling software to develop new insulin compounds.andP;  Theworkstation has 8 Mbytes of memory and a 1276 x 1000-pixelresolution.andP;  The software performs molecular dynamics withray-traced images.andP;  Novo recently used the system to create aninsulin molecule with a modified protein that acts faster thannaturally-occurring insulin.andP;  Novo hopes to explore thecapabilities of neural networks in the future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Novo-Nordisk A-S (computer programs)Silicon Graphics Inc. (products)Polygen Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    SGIC.andO;Product:   Silicon Graphics Iris 4D (0GT (Graphics system)_usage)Charmm (Computer graphics software) (usage).andO;Topic:     Computer GraphicsVisualizationComputer-Aided DesignGeneticsThree-Dimensional GraphicsGraphics SystemsModeling.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>